<p>This is a translation of a short piece of satire by famed author <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saadat_Hasan_Manto">Saadat Hasan Manto</a> (1912-1955), published in a collection titled <em>Manto‚Äôs Essays</em> <a class="citation" href="#manto_mazameen">[1]</a>. The original piece can be found on <a href="https://www.rekhta.org/articles/hindi-aur-urdu-saadat-hasan-manto-articles?lang=ur">Rekhta</a> in the Urdu alphabet, and a Nagari transliteration can be found <a href="/2018/12/12/%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%82%E0%A4%A6%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%94%E0%A4%B0-%E0%A4%89%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A6%E0%A5%82.html">here</a>. All footnotes were added in translation in order to explain some relevant background information.</p>
<p>But first, a whirlwind synopsis of the historical and linguistic background for those who may need it‚Ä¶</p>
<p><strong>Historical and Linguistic Background.</strong> After centuries of Persian influence via the Mughal courts, a language developed in South Asia. The core of the language (i.e., the grammatical structure and the bulk of the vocabulary) was decidedly Indo-Aryan, but loanwords from Persian (or from Arabic or Turkish via Persian) also abounded. The language was used both by court poets and by common folk of all creeds, especially in the Upper Gangetic Plains around Delhi. The orthography used to write a language is never a fundamental characteristic of the language itself, and certainly not in a society that is largely illiterate; in any case, the orthography that was usually used to write this language was a nativized variant of the Persian alphabet, adapted to meet some of the unique phonological needs of the language we‚Äôre discussing.</p>
<p>While one can clearly identify this language in the historical record, assigning a name to this language turns out to be a complicated task. Historically, a variety of names were used: among them are Hindavi, Hindi, Hindustani, Bhasha, Rekhta, Khari Boli, and Urdu. Furthermore, some of these names sometimes referred to closely related but different languages (such as Braj Bhasha or Avadhi). A detailed discussion of the confusion surrounding naming can be found in <a class="citation" href="#chand">[2 chap.¬ÝIII]</a>. In the 1800s, the name ‚ÄúUrdu‚Äù was in vogue.</p>
<p>Around this time, profound sectarianism began coursing through South Asia. The causes are unclear and manifold: fingers are often pointed at the influence of Christian missionaries and at the political structure of the British Raj, but many of the key figures of direct importance were native. In any case, one aspect of this sectarian pulse was a religious-nationalist movement related to the language we‚Äôve been discussing that picked up steam after the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Rebellion_of_1857">Indian Rebellion of 1857</a>. The goal of this movement was two-fold. The first goal was merely orthographic: the movement wanted for this language to be written in Nagari rather than the Urdu alphabet. The second goal was more substantial, and involved throwing out Persian loanwords and replacing them with words borrowed wholesale from Sanskrit (a language that had been dead in South Asia for many, many centuries, but that continued to hold religious significance for the Hindu population).</p>
<p>This movement began to push out propaganda describing Urdu as a language ‚Äúfor Muslims,‚Äù and decided to use the name ‚ÄúHindi‚Äù for the variant language they were championing, a language ‚Äúfor Hindus.‚Äù (In anticipation of the following piece of satire, it is worth pointing out at this point that even the name ‚ÄúHindi‚Äù itself is of Persian origin.) Adherents of this movement became the first of three camps in an intense ideological struggle; let us call this ‚ÄúCamp Hindi.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúCamp Urdu‚Äù presented an opposite reactionary vision. Adherents of this camp would attempt to eliminate all Indo-Aryan vocabulary from their writing and replace them with Persian loanwords, to the point that one could find ‚Äúwhole sentences in which the only Indian thing is the grammar, and with nothing but Persian words from beginning to end‚Äù <a class="citation" href="#grierson">[3 pp.¬Ý45 in vol.¬Ý9 pt.¬Ý1]</a>.</p>
<p>And then there was ‚ÄúCamp Hindustani,‚Äù the center of the spectrum spanned by Camp Hindi on one end and Camp Urdu on the other. They emphasized the language that was actually used by the masses, distinctly Indo-Aryan but with a healthy sprinkling of Persian loanwords. With the other two camps polarizing the usage of the names ‚ÄúHindi‚Äù and ‚ÄúUrdu,‚Äù some in Camp Hindustani tried to popularize the name ‚ÄúHindustani‚Äù to refer to this common core (but this was not universal: some people who used the terms ‚ÄúHindi‚Äù or ‚ÄúUrdu,‚Äù including Manto himself, would likely still be placed ideologically in Camp Hindustani). Some in Camp Hindustani also proposed a compromise orthographic system: both Nagari and the Urdu alphabet would be recognized scripts for writing this language, and students would be educated in both orthographic systems.</p>
<p>Needless to say, the above discussion simplifies a great deal, and the interested reader will find numerous and voluminous tomes written about the Hindi-Urdu fissure (e.g., <a class="citation" href="#king">[4]</a>, <a class="citation" href="#chand">[2]</a>, <a class="citation" href="#grierson">[3 vol.¬Ý9 pt.¬Ý1]</a>, among many others). In any case, by the 1940s, independence was looming just around the corner and questions about the ‚Äúnational language‚Äù of the soon-to-be-independent state(s) had brought this debate to the political forefront. The arguments reached fever pitch.</p>
<p>And then Partition befell the Subcontinent. The extremes won out politically: the vision of Camp Hindi became enshrined as one of the official languages of the Government of India (alongside English), and the vision of Camp Urdu became enshrined as one of the official languages of Pakistan (again, alongside English).</p>
<p>Of course, none of this intellectual and political brouhaha has had much bearing on the language as it used by the masses. Even today, speakers in India can largely understand speakers in Pakistan, and conversely, except when the diction becomes highly Sanskritized or highly Persianized. Perhaps the only significant impact of the Hindi-Urdu debates is that, since literacy rose substantially only after independence, most people on both sides of the border cannot read written work produced on the other side until it is transliterated.</p>
<p>The hysterical tenor and simultaneous pointlessness of the Hindi-Urdu debates is the object of satire in the following.</p>
