<p>The Hindi-Urdu squabble has been going on for an age. Maulvi<a href="#fn1" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref1"><sup>1</sup></a> Abdul Haq<a href="#fn2" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref2"><sup>2</sup></a>, Dr.¬ÝTara Chand<a href="#fn3" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref3"><sup>3</sup></a>, and Mahatma Gandhi<a href="#fn4" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref4"><sup>4</sup></a> all seem to understand this squabble, but it‚Äôs still completely beyond me. I‚Äôve tried, but I just can‚Äôt figure it out. Why are Hindus wasting their time talking about the Right of Hindi<a href="#fn5" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref5"><sup>5</sup></a>? Why are Muslims getting all worked up about the preservation of Urdu? Languages aren‚Äôt made, they simply arise; and no human efforts can eradicate them. I wanted to write something about this fresh and heated topic, and the result was the following dialogue.</p>
<p>Munshi<a href="#fn6" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref6"><sup>6</sup></a> Narayan Prashad: Iqbal Sahab<a href="#fn7" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref7"><sup>7</sup></a>, are you going to drink this club soda?</p>
<p>Mirza<a href="#fn8" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref8"><sup>8</sup></a> Mohammad Iqbal: Yes.</p>
<p>Munshi: Why don‚Äôt you drink lemon soda?</p>
<p>Iqbal: No reason, I just like club soda. It‚Äôs what everyone in my family drinks.</p>
<p>Munshi: So you hate lemon soda.</p>
<p>Iqbal: No‚Ä¶ Why would I hate it, Munshi Narayan Prashad? It‚Äôs just that everyone in my family drinks club soda, so I‚Äôve gotten used to it. It‚Äôs not a big deal, and actually I think that lemon soda is more enjoyable than club soda.</p>
<p>Munshi: That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm surprised. Why would you prefer an acrid drink over a sweet one? Lemon soda is not only sweet, it also smells nice. Don‚Äôt you think?</p>
<p>Iqbal: You‚Äôre absolutely right. But‚Ä¶</p>
<p>Munshi: But what?</p>
<p>Iqbal: Nothing‚Ä¶ I was just about to say that I‚Äôm going to have club soda anyway.</p>
<p>Munshi: Senseless! If someone was listening, they‚Äôd think I was forcing you to drink poison‚Ä¶ Come on, is there even any difference between lemon soda and club soda? The same factory makes both bottles. The same machine fills them both up. And besides, if you take the sweetness and the fragrance out of lemon soda, what would you be left with?</p>
<p>Iqbal: Club soda‚Ä¶ Acrid water‚Ä¶</p>
<p>Munshi: So what‚Äôs the problem with drinking lemon soda?</p>
<p>Iqbal: There‚Äôs no problem.</p>
<p>Munshi: Then go on, drink some.</p>
<p>Iqbal: What will you<a href="#fn9" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref9"><sup>9</sup></a> drink?</p>
<p>Munshi: I‚Äôll order another bottle.</p>
<p>Iqbal: Why would you order another bottle? What‚Äôs wrong with drinking my club soda?</p>
<p>Munshi: Th‚Ä¶ There‚Äôs no problem.</p>
<p>Iqbal: Then go on, drink some club soda.</p>
<p>Munshi: What will you<a href="#fn10" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref10"><sup>10</sup></a> drink?</p>
<p>Iqbal: I‚Äôll‚Ä¶ I‚Äôll order another bottle.</p>
<p>Munshi: Why will you order another bottle? What‚Äôs the problem with drinking lemon soda?</p>
<p>Iqbal: There‚Äôs‚Ä¶ no‚Ä¶ problem‚Ä¶ And what‚Äôs the problem with drinking club soda?</p>
<p>Munshi: There‚Äôs‚Ä¶ no‚Ä¶ problem.</p>
<p>Iqbal: It‚Äôs just that club soda is a little better.</p>
<p>Munshi: Lemon ‚Äî I think lemon soda is a little better.</p>
<p>Iqbal: That may be‚Ä¶ But I grew up hearing that club soda is better.</p>
<p>Munshi: Now what‚Ä¶ I also grew up hearing that lemon soda is better.</p>
<p>Iqbal: What‚Äôs <em>your</em><a href="#fn11" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref11"><sup>11</sup></a> opinion?</p>
<p>Munshi: What‚Äôs <em>your</em><a href="#fn12" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref12"><sup>12</sup></a> opinion?</p>
<p>Iqbal: My opinion‚Ä¶ My opinion‚Ä¶ I think that‚Ä¶ But why don‚Äôt you tell me what you think?</p>
<p>Munshi: My opinion‚Ä¶ My opinion‚Ä¶ I think that‚Ä¶ But why should I be the first one to say what I think?</p>
<p>Iqbal: No one‚Äôs going to say what they think this way‚Ä¶ Let‚Äôs just cover up our glasses so that we can take our time to settle this.</p>
<p>Munshi: We can‚Äôt do that‚Ä¶ The bottles have already been opened. Now we‚Äôll have to drink them. Let‚Äôs decide quickly. We don‚Äôt want them to go flat‚Ä¶ The entire point of soda is the carbonation.</p>
<p>Iqbal: I agree‚Ä¶ And you also accepted that there‚Äôs no difference between lemon soda and club soda.</p>
<p>Munshi: When did I say that there‚Äôs no difference? There‚Äôs a lot of difference‚Ä¶ A world of difference. One is sweet and sour and smells nice. That‚Äôs three things it has more of than club soda. Club soda is just carbonation, and the carbonation is so strong that you feel it in your nose. Lemon soda is just more enjoyable. You drink a bottle, and you feel good for hours afterwards. Only invalids drink club soda‚Ä¶ Besides, you just accepted that lemon soda is more enjoyable than club soda.</p>
<p>Iqbal: Okay. But I didn‚Äôt say that it‚Äôs <em>better</em> than club soda. Enjoyable doesn‚Äôt mean that it‚Äôs good for you. Pickles<a href="#fn13" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref13"><sup>13</sup></a> are enjoyable but you surely know how bad they are for you. Just because a thing is sour and smells nice doesn‚Äôt make it obviously a good thing. Just ask any doctor and he‚Äôll tell you that lemon soda is bad for your stomach.</p>
<p>Munshi: Look, I think the only way to settle this is to mix the two of them together.</p>
<p>Iqbal: Sounds good to me.</p>
<p>Munshi: Pour half of the club soda into this empty glass.</p>
<p>Iqbal: Why don‚Äôt you put half of the lemon soda in the glass‚Ä¶ I‚Äôll put the club soda in afterwards.</p>
<p>Munshi: That doesn‚Äôt make any sense. Why don‚Äôt you pour the club soda in first?</p>
<p>Iqbal: I want club soda mixed with lemon soda.</p>
<p>Munshi: And I want lemon soda mixed with club soda.</p>
